{{About|the nuclear weapon|the alternative rock musician|Melissa Auf der Maur}}
[[File:Medium Atomic Demolition Munition (with scientists).jpg|thumb|Scientists look at a MADM nuclear land mine. Cutaway casing with warhead inside, code-decoder / firing unit is at left.]]
[[File:Medium Atomic Demolition Munition (internal).jpg|thumb|Internal components of the MADM setup. From left to right: packing container, [[W45]] warhead, code-decoder unit, firing unit.]]
'''Medium Atomic Demolition Munition''' ('''MADM''') was a [[tactical nuclear weapon]] developed by the [[United States]] during the [[Cold War]]. They were designed to be used as [[Atomic demolition munition|nuclear land mines]] and for other tactical purposes, with a relatively low [[nuclear weapon yield|explosive yield]] from a [[W45]] warhead, between 1 and 15 [[kiloton]]s. Each MADM weighed less than 400&nbsp;lb (181&nbsp;kg) total. They were deployed between 1965 and 1986.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20060318020109/http://www.brook.edu/FP/projects/nucwcost/madm.htm Atomic Demolition Munitions] by Brookings Institution], archived copy</ref>

